[1] UK: (England) sheep, 1st cases
Date: 23 Jan 2012
From: Trevor Drew <Trevor.Drew@ahvla.gsi.gov.uk>

Following the emergence of Schmallenberg virus in some countries in continental Europe, enhanced surveillance has been in place in the UK, since the autumn of 2011. A number of samples have been submitted to AHVLA for testing for Schmallenberg virus as part of this surveillance

We have identified the Schmallenberg virus in some of these samples, submitted recently. These samples were from lambs born with deformities similar to case descriptions from cases in continental Europe. The location of the positive cases are the counties of Norfolk, Suffolk and East Sussex, in the south-east corner of the country and this is consistent with airborne transmission via insects blown across the
English Channel, from countries we now know to have been infected last autumn. No cases in bovines have been detected.

Further details on can be found on our website at www.defra.gov.uk/ahvla

We gratefully acknowledge the assistance of scientists in affected countries in Europe and, particularly, the Fredreich Loeffler Institute in providing information on primer sequences and probe used for their diagnostic PCR and for making further sequence information available. Using this data, our own sequence analysis of the S gene and L gene of the virus detected in GB cases conclusively demonstrates it to be the
same virus.

We will continue to collaborate with FLI and other laboratories in Europe to ensure a rapid and coordinated approach to understanding the disease and its impact, the causative virus, risk pathways and methods of diagnosis and control.

--
Prof Trevor Drew MSc PhD CBiol MSB
Statutory & Exotic Viral Diseases Programme Manager; Head of Virology=20
Animal Health and Veterinary Laboratories Agency (AHVLA) Weybridge
Woodham Lane, New Haw
