[4] Russia: temporary import restrictions
Date: Wed 18 Jan 2012
Source: Rosselkhoznadzor (Federal Service for Veterinary and
Phytosanitary Surveillance) News [edited]
http://fsvps.ru/fsvps/news/4046.html?_language=en


Mortality in cattle and small ruminants was reported on a number of Dutch, German, and Belgium farms, as the World Organization for Animal Health officially reports. Symptoms of the disease included fever, diarrhea, and drop in milk yields. Potential agent of the disease (Schmallenberg virus) [SBV] was recovered in the Friedrich Loeffler Institute (FLI) (the National Research Centre for Animal Health in Germany). The virus was determined to have an ability to cause congenital defects in calves and lambs including neck dislocation, hydrocephaly, deformities of joints, premature birth, and abortions.

Therefore, Deputy Head of the Rosselkhoznadzor and Chief Veterinary Officer, Nicolai Vlasov, applied to Director General of the Directorate-General for Health and Consumers of the European Commission, Paola Testori Coggi, for information on characteristics of the agent, its stability, routes of spread, routes of transmission among animals, ways of prevention, diagnosis, existing diagnostic
kits, and on measures taken by the Official Veterinary Services of the EU-countries to prevent spread of the disease during export of cattle and small ruminants, meat products, offal, semen, and embryos to the 3rd countries, including Russia and other CU-countries.

On 17 Jan 2012 the Rosselkhoznadzor imposed temporary restrictions on import of live small ruminants, meat, offal, semen, and embryos of small ruminants from Germany, the Netherlands, and Belgium to Russia, until the current situation is cleared up.

--
