[The UK has become Europe's 4th country infected by the Orthobunyavirus "Schmallenberg virus" (SBV), a teratogenic, most likely vector-borne virus initially identified by FLI scientists in December 2011. So far, SBV has been identified in congenitally malformed offspring of domestic ruminants in Germany, the Netherlands, and Belgium. The spread of this virus resembles, geographically and seasons-wise, the one manifested by the culicoid-borne orbivirus BTV-8 in the late summer of 2006. Eventually, BTV-8 spread in a southward direction within western Europe.

It will interesting to note if (and, in case affirmative, when) disease symptoms, similar to the ones seen in Germany and the Netherlands in August-October 2011, have also been observed in Eastern England. The UK's sheep population is rather dense, and if the introduction of SBV coincided with the 1st semester of pregnancy in ewes, losses might be severe.

The Dutch figures, as updated at noon 23 Jan 2012, are:
Total number of tested holdings - 207 (all species; out of 283 holdings from which samples have been derived; 76 still investigated).
cattle: tested 91, positive 2* (2.2 percent)
sheep: tested 107, positive 72 (67.3 percent)
goats: tested 9, positive 2 (22.2 percent).
*These are the 1st SBV positive bovines in the Netherlands. One of them is from the province of Drenthe, the other one from Flevoland. See table at http://www.vwa.nl/txmpub/files/?p_file_id=2201855 and a map at http://www.vwa.nl/txmpub/files/?p_file_id=2201854 (sheep/goat foci -- red, cattle -- blue).

The countryside German press provides data on a large number of sheep holdings in which SBV positive congenitally affected lambs have been identified; a country-wide summarised information is anticipated.

To follow this unfolding event, thus far recorded in Germany, the Netherlands, Belgium, and the UK (England), it would be helpful if a regional map, indicating all identified SBV holdings, becomes available. Such a map was developed and kept updated by the EU animal-health authorities during the BTV-8 epizootic, which started in the summer of 2006 and continued during the consecutive years. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1lNY.]
